ated Schumann’s text and arranged it into four thematic sections: “On being a musician,” “Playing,” “Practicing,” and “Composing.” Each page is decoratively designed, and accompanying Schumann’s original "ation are Isserlis’s thoughtful and often humorous glosses. The book concludes with Isserlis’s own reflections on his life as a musician and performer: “My Own Bits of Advice (For What They’re Worth).” The result is a unique and thought-provoking book that will be treasured by aspiring musicians of any age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMusicvMiscellanea. 0aMusicvQuotations, maxims, etc. 0aMusicxPerformancevMiscellanea. 0aMusicxPerformancevQuotations, maxims, etc. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  amusical education, classical music, performance, composition, practice, musicians, training, rehearsal, cellist, cello, symphony, orchestra, advice, gift, nonfiction, biography, humor, illustrations, children, skills, notes, scales, chords, guide, reference, instrument, violin, piano, woodwinds, strings, harp, youth, percussion, fame.1 aIsserlis, Steven, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIsserlis, Steven.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226482880423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226482880/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles